claim: The COVID-19 vaccine causes bad alergic reactions.
label: FALSE

claim: A news article claims 30% of Ukrainian patients who participated in an American COVID-19 vaccine trial died. The test took place in the area of Lugansk, an Ukrainian separatist region
label: FALSE

claim: People will be vaccinated against COVID-19 by force.
label: No evidence

claim: A volunteer for Coronavac, a Chinese vaccine against COVID-19 being tested in Brazil, reported severe fevers in a story published by Marie Claire magazine.
label: FALSE

claim: Brazilian CoronaVac volunteer reported body pain and fever after vaccination.
label: FALSE

claim: Multiple posts shared hundreds of times on Facebook and Twitter claim that four Ukrainian soldiers died after participating in American COVID-19 vaccine trials in the northeastern Ukrainian city of Kharkiv. The claim, published in several languages across different posts, was attributed to a police spokesperson in the self-proclaimed Lugansk People’s Republic.
label: FALSE

claim: Publications that state that “the new vaccine contains digitizable ‘RNA’”, an alleged “replicant that is activated by 5G” and that is why “the virus can be reactivated after the patient recovers”
label: FALSE

claim: A Facebook post claims the recovery rate from COVID-19 is “99.9 per cent”, and claims there is a choice between getting the disease and getting “the vaccine with an 80 per cent adverse reaction rate”.
label: FALSE

claim: Oxford University has a vaccine which has been scientifically proven to work against COVID-19.
label: MISLEADING

claim: A meme claims that Bill Gates was “expelled from India for leaving 47,000 permanently disabled and disabled children, a direct result of his polio vaccine.”
